Example 1

(a) Prove by deduction: "If $x < -5$ then $x^2 > 25$."

(b) Explain why the converse is not true.

Solutions:

(a) If $x < -5$ then $|x| > 5$ {geometric definition of absolute value}
$\therefore |x|^2 > 5^2$ {squaring both sides}
$\therefore x^2 > 25$ {$|x|^2 = x^2$}

(b) The converse would be: "If $x^2 > 25$ then $x < -5$."
This is not necessarily true because $6^2 > 25$, but $6 > -5$.

Proof:

$0 = 0 + 0$
$\therefore 0 \times x = (0 + 0) \times x$ {multiplying both sides by $x$}
$\therefore 0 \times x = 0 \times x + 0 \times x$ {Axiom 3}
$\therefore 0 \times x + (-(0 \times x)) = (0 \times x + 0 \times x) + (-(0 \times x))$ {adding the additive inverse of $0 \times x$}
$\therefore 0 \times x + (-(0 \times x)) = (0 \times x) + [0 \times x + (-(0 \times x))]$ {Axiom 1}
$\therefore 0 = 0 \times x + 0$
$\therefore 0 = 0 \times x$ {Axiom 4}
$\therefore 0 \times x = 0 = x \times 0$ {Axiom 2}
